# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adaptive-immunity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The **adaptive immune system** (**AIS**), also known as the **acquired immune system** or **specific immune system**, is a subsystem of the immune system that is composed of specialized cells, organs, and processes that eliminate pathogens specifically.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system is one of the two main immunity strategies found in vertebrates (the other being the innate immune system).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Like the innate system, the adaptive immune system includes both humoral immunity components and cell-mediated immunity components and destroys invading pathogens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Unlike the innate immune system, which is pre-programmed to react to common broad categories of pathogen, the adaptive immune system is highly specific to each particular pathogen the body has encountered.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Adaptive immunity creates immunological memory after an initial response to a specific pathogen, and leads to an enhanced response to future encounters with that pathogen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies are a critical part of the adaptive immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Adaptive immunity can provide long-lasting protection, sometimes for the person's entire lifetime.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] For example, someone who recovers from measles is now protected against measles for their lifetime; in other cases it does not provide lifetime protection, as with chickenpox.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This process of adaptive immunity is the basis of vaccination.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The cells that carry out the adaptive immune response are white blood cells known as lymphocytes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] B cells and T cells, two different types of lymphocytes, carry out the main activities: antibody responses, and cell-mediated immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In antibody responses, B cells are activated to secrete antibodies, which are proteins also known as immunoglobulins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies travel through the bloodstream and bind to the foreign antigen causing it to inactivate, which does not allow the antigen to bind to the host.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Antigens are any substances that elicit the adaptive immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Sometimes the adaptive system is unable to distinguish harmful from harmless foreign molecules; the effects of this may be hayfever, asthma, or any other allergy.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In adaptive immunity, pathogen-specific receptors are "acquired" during the lifetime of the organism (whereas in innate immunity pathogen-specific receptors are already encoded in the genome).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This acquired response is called "adaptive" because it prepares the body's immune system for future challenges (though it can actually also be maladaptive when it results in allergies or autoimmunity).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The system is highly adaptable because of two factors.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] First, somatic hypermutation is a process of accelerated random genetic mutations in the antibody-coding genes, which allows antibodies with novel specificity to be created.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Second, V(D)J recombination randomly selects one variable (V), one diversity (D), and one joining (J) region for genetic recombination and discards the rest, which produces a highly unique combination of antigen-receptor gene segments in each lymphocyte.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This mechanism allows a small number of genetic segments to generate a vast number of different antigen receptors, which are then uniquely expressed on each individual lymphocyte.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Since the gene rearrangement leads to an irreversible change in the DNA of each cell, all progeny (offspring) of that cell inherit genes that encode the same receptor specificity, including the memory B cells and memory T cells that are the keys to long-lived specific immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The term "adaptive" was first used by Robert Good in reference to antibody responses in frogs as a synonym for "acquired immune response" in 1964.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Good acknowledged he used the terms as synonyms but explained only that he preferred to use the term "adaptive".
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The term "adaptive" as used in immunology is problematic as acquired immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the physiological sense.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Indeed, both acquired and innate immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the evolutionary sense.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Most textbooks today, following the early use by Janeway, use "adaptive" almost exclusively and noting in glossaries that the term is synonymous with "acquired".
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The classic sense of "acquired immunity" came to mean, since Tonegawa's discovery, "antigen-specific immunity mediated by somatic gene rearrangements that create clone-defining antigen receptors".
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In the last decade, the term "adaptive" has been increasingly applied to another class of immune response not so-far associated with somatic gene rearrangements.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These include expansion of natural killer (NK) cells with so-far unexplained specificity for antigens, expansion of NK cells expressing germ-line encoded receptors, and activation of other innate immune cells to an activated state that confers a short-term "immune memory".
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In this sense, "adaptive immunity" more closely resembles the concept of "activated state" or "heterostasis", thus returning in sense to the physiological sense of "adaptation" to environmental changes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Acquired immunity is triggered in vertebrates when a pathogen evades the innate immune system and (1) generates a threshold level of antigen and (2) generates "stranger" or "danger" signals activating dendritic cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In humans, it takes 4–7 days for the adaptive immune system to mount a significant response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] T and B lymphocytes are the cells of the adaptive immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The human body has about 2 trillion lymphocytes, which are 20–40% of white blood cells; their total mass is about the same as the brain or liver.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The peripheral bloodstream contains only 2% of all circulating lymphocytes; the other 98% move within tissues and the lymphatic system, which includes the lymph nodes and spleen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In humans, approximately 1–2% of the lymphocyte pool recirculates each hour to increase the opportunity for the cells to encounter the specific pathogen and antigen that they react to.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] B cells and T cells are derived from the same multipotent hematopoietic stem cells, and look identical to one another until after they are activated.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] B cells play a large role in the humoral immune response, whereas T cells are intimately involved in cell-mediated immune responses.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In all vertebrates except Agnatha, B cells and T cells are produced by stem cells in the bone marrow.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] T cell progenitors then migrate from the bone marrow to the thymus, where they develop further.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Acquired immunity relies on the capacity of immune cells to distinguish between the body's own cells and unwanted invaders.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The host's cells express "self" antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These antigens are different from those on the surface of bacteria or on the surface of virus-infected host cells ("non-self" or "foreign" antigens).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune response is triggered by recognizing foreign antigen in the cellular context of an activated dendritic cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), all cells are capable of presenting antigen through the function of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Some cells are specially equipped to present antigen, and to prime naive T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Dendritic cells, B-cells, and macrophages are equipped with special "co-stimulatory" ligands recognized by co-stimulatory receptors on T cells, and are termed professional antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Several T cells subgroups can be activated by professional APCs, and each type of T cell is specially equipped to deal with each unique toxin or microbial pathogen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The type of T cell activated, and the type of response generated, depends, in part, on the context in which the APC first encountered the antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Dendritic cells engulf exogenous pathogens, such as bacteria, parasites or toxins in the tissues and then migrate, via chemotactic signals, to the T cell-enriched lymph nodes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] During migration, dendritic cells undergo a process of maturation in which they lose most of their ability to engulf other pathogens, and develop an ability to communicate with T-cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The dendritic cell uses enzymes to chop the pathogen into smaller pieces, called antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In the lymph node, the dendritic cell displays these non-self antigens on its surface by coupling them to a receptor called the major histocompatibility complex, or MHC (also known in humans as human leukocyte antigen (HLA)).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This MHC-antigen complex is recognized by T-cells passing through the lymph node.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Exogenous antigens are usually displayed on MHC class II molecules, which activate CD4+T helper cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Endogenous antigens are produced by intracellular bacteria and viruses replicating within a host cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The host cell uses enzymes to digest virally associated proteins and displays these pieces on its surface to T-cells by coupling them to MHC.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Endogenous antigens are typically displayed on MHC class I molecules, and activate CD8+ cytotoxic T-cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), MHC class I is expressed by all host cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Cytotoxic T cells (also known as TC, cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs), or killer T cells) are a sub-group of T cells that induce the death of cells that are infected with viruses (and other pathogens), or are otherwise damaged or dysfunctional.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Naive cytotoxic T cells are activated when their T-cell receptor (TCR) strongly interacts with a peptide-bound MHC class I molecule.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This affinity depends on the type and orientation of the antigen/MHC complex, and is what keeps the CTL and infected cell bound together.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Once activated, the CTL undergoes a process called clonal selection, in which it gains functions and divides rapidly to produce an army of "armed" effector cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The activated CTL then travels throughout the body searching for cells that bear that unique MHC class I + peptide.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] When exposed to these infected or dysfunctional somatic cells, effector CTLs release perforin and granulysin: cytotoxins that form pores in the target cell's plasma membrane, allowing ions and water to flow into the infected cell and causing it to burst or lyse.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] CTLs release granzyme, a serine protease encapsulated in a granule that enters cells via pores to induce apoptosis (cell death).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] To limit extensive tissue damage during an infection, CTL activation is tightly controlled and in general requires a very strong MHC/antigen activation signal, or additional activation signals provided by "helper" T-cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] On resolution of the infection, most effector cells die and phagocytes clear them away—but a few of these cells remain as memory cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] On a later encounter with the same antigen, these memory cells quickly differentiate into effector cells, dramatically shortening the time required to mount an effective response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] CD4+ lymphocytes, also called "helper" T cells, are immune response mediators, and play an important role in establishing and maximizing the capabilities of the acquired immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These cells have no cytotoxic or phagocytic activity; and cannot kill infected cells or clear pathogens, but, in essence "manage" the immune response, by directing other cells to perform these tasks.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T cells express T cell receptors (TCR) that recognize antigen bound to Class II MHC molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The activation of a naive helper T-cell causes it to release cytokines, which influences the activity of many cell types, including the APC (Antigen-Presenting Cell) that activated it.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T-cells require a much milder activation stimulus than cytotoxic T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T cells can provide extra signals that "help" activate cytotoxic cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Classically, two types of effector CD4+ T helper cell responses can be induced by a professional APC, designated Th1 and Th2, each designed to eliminate different types of pathogens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The factors that dictate whether an infection triggers a Th1 or Th2 type response are not fully understood, but the response generated does play an important role in the clearance of different pathogens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The Th1 response is characterized by the production of Interferon-gamma, which activates the bactericidal activities of macrophages, and induces B cells to make opsonizing (marking for phagocytosis) and complement-fixing antibodies, and leads to *cell-mediated immunity*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In general, Th1 responses are more effective against intracellular pathogens (viruses and bacteria that are inside host cells).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The Th2 response is characterized by the release of Interleukin 5, which induces eosinophils in the clearance of parasites.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Th2 also produce Interleukin 4, which facilitates B cell isotype switching.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In general, Th2 responses are more effective against extracellular bacteria, parasites including helminths and toxins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Like cytotoxic T cells, most of the CD4+ helper cells die on resolution of infection, with a few remaining as CD4+ memory cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Increasingly, there is strong evidence from mouse and human-based scientific studies of a broader diversity in CD4+ effector T helper cell subsets.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Regulatory T (Treg) cells, have been identified as important negative regulators of adaptive immunity as they limit and suppress the immune system to control aberrant immune responses to self-antigens; an important mechanism in controlling the development of autoimmune diseases.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Follicular helper T (Tfh) cells are another distinct population of effector CD4+ T cells that develop from naive T cells post-antigen activation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Tfh cells are specialized in helping B cell humoral immunity as they are uniquely capable of migrating to follicular B cells in secondary lymphoid organs and provide them positive paracrine signals to enable the generation and recall production of high-quality affinity-matured antibodies.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Similar to Tregs, Tfh cells also play a role in immunological tolerance as an abnormal expansion of Tfh cell numbers can lead to unrestricted autoreactive antibody production causing severe systemic autoimmune disorders.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The relevance of CD4+ T helper cells is highlighted during an HIV infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] HIV is able to subvert the immune system by specifically attacking the CD4+ T cells, precisely the cells that could drive the clearance of the virus, but also the cells that drive immunity against all other pathogens encountered during an organism's lifetime.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) possess an alternative T cell receptor (TCR) as opposed to CD4+ and CD8+ αβ T cells and share characteristics of helper T cells, cytotoxic T cells and natural killer cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Like other 'unconventional' T cell subsets bearing invariant TCRs, such as CD1d-restricted natural killer T cells, γδ T cells exhibit characteristics that place them at the border between innate and acquired immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] On one hand, γδ T cells may be considered a component of adaptive immunity in that they rearrange TCR genes via V(D)J recombination, which also produces junctional diversity, and develop a memory phenotype.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] On the other hand, however, the various subsets may also be considered part of the innate immune system where a restricted TCR or NK receptors may be used as a pattern recognition receptor.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] For example, according to this paradigm, large numbers of Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells respond within hours to common molecules produced by microbes, and highly restricted intraepithelial Vδ1 T cells respond to stressed epithelial cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] B Cells are the major cells involved in the creation of antibodies that circulate in blood plasma and lymph, known as humoral immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies (also known as immunoglobulin, Ig), are large Y-shaped proteins used by the immune system to identify and neutralize foreign objects.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In mammals, there are five types of antibody: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, differing in biological properties; each has evolved to handle different kinds of antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Upon activation, B cells produce antibodies, each of which recognize a unique antigen, and neutralizing specific pathogens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Like the T cell, B cells express a unique B cell receptor (BCR), in this case, a membrane-bound antibody molecule.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] All the BCR of any one clone of B cells recognizes and binds to only one particular antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] A critical difference between B cells and T cells is how each cell "sees" an antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] T cells recognize their cognate antigen in a processed form – as a peptide in the context of an MHC molecule, whereas B cells recognize antigens in their native form.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Once a B cell encounters its cognate (or specific) antigen (and receives additional signals from a helper T cell (predominately Th2 type)), it further differentiates into an effector cell, known as a plasma cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Plasma cells are short-lived cells (2–3 days) that secrete antibodies.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These antibodies bind to antigens, making them easier targets for phagocytes, and trigger the complement cascade.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] About 10% of plasma cells survive to become long-lived antigen-specific memory B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Already primed to produce specific antibodies, these cells can be called upon to respond quickly if the same pathogen re-infects the host, while the host experiences few, if any, symptoms.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Primitive jawless vertebrates, such as the lamprey and hagfish, have an adaptive immune system that shows 3 different cell lineages, each sharing a common origin with B cells, αβ T cells, and innate-like γΔ T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Instead of the classical antibodies and T cell receptors, these animals possess a large array of molecules called variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs for short) that, like the antigen receptors of jawed vertebrates, are produced from only a small number (one or two) of genes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These molecules are believed to bind pathogenic antigens in a similar way to antibodies, and with the same degree of specificity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] For a long time it was thought that insects and other invertebrates possess only innate immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] However, in recent years some of the basic hallmarks of adaptive immunity have been discovered in insects.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Those traits are immune memory and specificity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Although the hallmarks are present the mechanisms are different from those in vertebrates.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Immune memory in insects was discovered through the phenomenon of priming.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] When insects are exposed to non-lethal dose or heat killed bacteria they are able to develop a memory of that infection that allows them to withstand otherwise lethal dose of the same bacteria they were exposed to before.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Unlike in vertebrates, insects do not possess cells specific for adaptive immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Instead those mechanisms are mediated by hemocytes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Hemocytes function similarly to phagocytes and after priming they are able to more effectively recognize and engulf the pathogen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] It was also shown that it is possible to transfer the memory into offspring.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] For example, in honeybees if the queen is infected with bacteria then the newly born workers have enhanced abilities in fighting with the same bacteria.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Other experimental model based on red flour beetle also showed pathogen specific primed memory transfer into offspring from both mothers and fathers.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The most commonly accepted theory of this specificity is based on the *Dscam* gene.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The *Dscam* gene, which mediates phagocytosis in some insects, contains three variable Ig domains.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These domains can be alternatively spliced, producing a large number of possible isoforms.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] It has been shown that after exposure to different pathogens, different isoforms of Dscam are produced, and that these isoforms associate and defend against bacteria in an isoform-specific manner.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Another mechanism that supports the specificity of insect immunity is RNA interference (RNAi).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] RNAi is a form of antiviral immunity with high specificity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] It has several different pathways that all end with the virus being unable to replicate.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] One of the pathways is siRNA in which long double stranded RNA is cut into pieces that serve as templates for protein complex Ago2-RISC that finds and degrades complementary RNA of the virus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] MiRNA pathway in cytoplasm binds to Ago1-RISC complex and functions as a template for viral RNA degradation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Last one is piRNA where small RNA binds to the Piwi protein family and controls transposones and other mobile elements.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Despite the research the exact mechanisms responsible for immune priming and specificity in insects are not well described.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] CRISPR has a lot of short repeated sequences.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These sequences are part of an adaptive immune system for prokaryotes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] It allows them to remember and counter the bacteriophages which prey on them.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] They work as a kind of acquired immune system for bacteria.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] When B cells and T cells are activated some become memory B cells and some memory T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Throughout the lifetime of an animal these memory cells form a database of effective B and T lymphocytes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Upon interaction with a previously encountered antigen, the appropriate memory cells are selected and activated.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In this manner, the second and subsequent exposures to an antigen produce a stronger and faster immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This is "adaptive" in the sense that the body's immune system prepares itself for future challenges, but is "maladaptive" of course if the receptors are autoimmune.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Immunological memory can be in the form of either *passive* short-term memory or *active* long-term memory.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Passive memory is usually short-term, lasting between a few days and several months.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Newborn infants have had no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] *In utero*, maternal IgG is transported directly across the placenta, so that, at birth, human babies have high levels of antibodies, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Breast milk contains antibodies (mainly IgA) that are transferred to the gut of the infant, protecting against bacterial infections, until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies: It only borrows them.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Short-term passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another via antibody-rich serum.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In general, active immunity is long-term and can be acquired by infection followed by B cell and T cell activation, or artificially acquired by vaccines, in a process called immunization.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Historically, infectious disease has been the leading cause of death in the human population.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Over the last century, two important factors have been developed to combat their spread: sanitation and immunization.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Immunization (commonly referred to as vaccination) is the deliberate induction of an immune response, and represents the single most effective manipulation of the immune system that scientists have developed.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Immunizations are successful because they utilize the immune system's natural specificity as well as its inducibility.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The principle behind immunization is to introduce an antigen, derived from a disease-causing organism, that stimulates the immune system to develop protective immunity against that organism, but that does not itself cause the pathogenic effects of that organism.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] An antigen (short for *anti*body *gen*erator), is defined as any substance that binds to a specific antibody and elicits an adaptive immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Most viral vaccines are based on live attenuated viruses, whereas many bacterial vaccines are based on acellular components of microorganisms, including harmless toxin components.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Many antigens derived from acellular vaccines do not strongly induce an adaptive response, and most bacterial vaccines require the addition of *adjuvants* that activate the antigen-presenting cells of the innate immune system to enhance immunogenicity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Most large molecules, including virtually all proteins and many polysaccharides, can serve as antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The parts of an antigen that interact with an antibody molecule or a lymphocyte receptor, are called epitopes, or antigenic determinants.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Most antigens contain a variety of epitopes and can stimulate the production of antibodies, specific T cell responses, or both.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] A very small proportion (less than 0.01%) of the total lymphocytes are able to bind to a particular antigen, which suggests that only a few cells respond to each antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Even in the absence of antigen stimulation, a human can produce more than 1 trillion different antibody molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Millions of genes would be required to store the genetic information that produces these receptors, but, the entire human genome contains fewer than 25,000 genes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Myriad receptors are produced through a process known as clonal selection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] According to the clonal selection theory, at birth, an animal randomly generates a vast diversity of lymphocytes (each bearing a unique antigen receptor) from information encoded in a small family of genes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] To generate each unique antigen receptor, these genes have undergone a process called V(D)J recombination, or *combinatorial diversification*, in which one gene segment recombines with other gene segments to form a single unique gene.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This assembly process generates the enormous diversity of receptors and antibodies, before the body ever encounters antigens, and enables the immune system to respond to an almost unlimited diversity of antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Throughout an animal's lifetime, lymphocytes that can react against the antigens an animal actually encounters are selected for action—directed against anything that expresses that antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The innate and acquired portions of the immune system work together, not in spite of each other.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired arm, B, and T cells could not function without the innate system input.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] T cells are useless without antigen-presenting cells to activate them, and B cells are disabled without T cell help.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] On the other hand, the innate system would likely be overrun with pathogens without the specialized action of the adaptive immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The cornerstone of the immune system is the recognition of "self" versus "non-self".
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Therefore, the mechanisms that protect the human fetus (which is considered "non-self") from attack by the immune system, are particularly interesting.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Although no comprehensive explanation has emerged to explain this mysterious, and often repeated, lack of rejection, two classical reasons may explain how the fetus is tolerated.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The first is that the fetus occupies a portion of the body protected by a non-immunological barrier, the uterus, which the immune system does not routinely patrol.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The second is that the fetus itself may promote local immunosuppression in the mother, perhaps by a process of active nutrient depletion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] A more modern explanation for this induction of tolerance is that specific glycoproteins expressed in the uterus during pregnancy suppress the uterine immune response (see eu-FEDS).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] During pregnancy in viviparous mammals (all mammals except Monotremes), endogenous retroviruses (ERVs) are activated and produced in high quantities during the implantation of the embryo.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] They are currently known to possess immunosuppressive properties, suggesting a role in protecting the embryo from its mother's immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The immunodepressive action was the initial normal behavior of the virus, similar to HIV.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The fusion proteins were a way to spread the infection to other cells by simply merging them with the infected one (HIV does this too).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] It is believed that the ancestors of modern viviparous mammals evolved after an infection by this virus, enabling the fetus to survive the immune system of the mother.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The human genome project found several thousand ERVs classified into 24 families.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This theory, which builds on the existing clonal selection hypothesis and since 1974 has been developed mainly by Niels Jerne and Geoffrey W.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Hoffmann, is seen as being relevant to the understanding of the HIV pathogenesis and the search for an HIV vaccine.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] One of the most interesting developments in biomedical science during the past few decades has been elucidation of mechanisms mediating innate immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] One set of innate immune mechanisms is humoral, such as complement activation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Another set comprises pattern recognition receptors such as toll-like receptors, which induce the production of interferons and other cytokines increasing resistance of cells such as monocytes to infections.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Cytokines produced during innate immune responses are among the activators of adaptive immune responses.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies exert additive or synergistic effects with mechanisms of innate immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Unstable HbS clusters Band-3, a major integral red cell protein; antibodies recognize these clusters and accelerate their removal by phagocytic cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Clustered Band 3 proteins with attached antibodies activate complement, and complement C3 fragments are opsonins recognized by the CR1 complement receptor on phagocytic cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] A population study has shown that the protective effect of the sickle-cell trait against falciparum malaria involves the augmentation of acquired as well as innate immune responses to the malaria parasite, illustrating the expected transition from innate to acquired immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Repeated malaria infections strengthen acquired immunity and broaden its effects against parasites expressing different surface antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] By school age most children have developed efficacious adaptive immunity against malaria.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These observations raise questions about mechanisms that favor the survival of most children in Africa while allowing some to develop potentially lethal infections.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In malaria, as in other infections, innate immune responses lead into, and stimulate, adaptive immune responses.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The genetic control of innate and acquired immunity is now a large and flourishing discipline.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Humoral and cell-mediated immune responses limit malaria parasite multiplication, and many cytokines contribute to the pathogenesis of malaria as well as to the resolution of infections.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system evolved as an elaboration of the innate immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Lymphoid cells can be identified in some pre-vertebrate deuterostomes (i.e., sea urchins).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The amphioxus is a chordate like all vertebrates.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Its genome includes many building blocks of the adaptive immune system, but none of the true hallmarks such as somatic recombination.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] There is, however, considerable expansion in LRR genes and immunoglobulin-fold genes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] There is high polymorphism among different individuals, an example of diversity in the innate immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system, which has been best-studied in mammals, originated in jawed fish approximately 500 million years ago.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Most of the molecules, cells, tissues, and associated mechanisms of this system of defense are found in cartilaginous fishes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Lymphocyte receptors, Ig and TCR, are found in all jawed vertebrates.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The most ancient Ig class, IgM, is membrane-bound and then secreted upon stimulation of cartilaginous fish B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Another isotype, shark IgW, is related to mammalian IgD.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] TCRs, both α/β and γ/δ, are found in jawed fish (cladistically including mammals).
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Most elements of the jawed fish system are in place thanks to the second round of whole-genome duplication (2R) that the jawed fish have undergone, providing an expanded repertoire of immune-related genes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The immunoprotease genes involved in antigen processing and presentation as well as the class I and class II genes, are closely linked within the MHC of almost all studied species.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] These systems, along with RAG, were set in place quickly after 2R had happened.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The MHC region is paralogous to the Ig/TCR region.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Comparing paralogous regions allow for the reconstruction of a *primordial immune complex*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The cartilaginous fish system does have one critical difference compared to the system of bony fish (including mammals): the gene segments that undergo V(D)J recombination in bony fish are not organized in huge clusters like they are in bony fish.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Instead, these parts are arranged as "miniclusters" and rearrangement by RAG is largely limited within these clusters.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] As a result, not as many combinations are available compared to bony fish.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The RAG transposon likely invaded a "UrIg2" immunoglobin gene, which had an unsplit VJ, in an ancestor of all extant jawed fish.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Splitting the V and J exons is adaptive, as it enables greater variation through changing the size of the CDR3 loop.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] This feature is inherited by all the descendants of UrIg2 such as Ig and TCR.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The jawless fish are vertebrates like the jawed fish, but belong on a different branch.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] In jawless fish, three subsets of lymphocytes use variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs) for antigen binding.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The VLRs are derived from pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) of the innate immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Diversity is generated by a cytosine deaminase-mediated rearrangement of LRR-based DNA segments.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] The functional dichotomy between two of the lymphocyte subsets parallels Ig and TCR molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Immunity can be acquired either actively or passively.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Immunity is acquired actively when a person is exposed to foreign substances and the immune system responds.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Passive immunity is when antibodies are transferred from one host to another.
[src:adaptive-immunity/adaptive-immune-system] Both actively acquired and passively acquired immunity can be obtained by natural or artificial means.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Cytotoxic T cells (also known as Tc, killer T cell, or cytotoxic T-lymphocyte (CTL)) express CD8 co-receptors and are a population of T cells that are specialized for inducing programmed cell death of other cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Cytotoxic T cells regularly patrol all body cells to maintain the organismal homeostasis.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Whenever they encounter signs of disease, caused for example by the presence of viruses or intracellular bacteria or a transformed tumor cell, they initiate processes to destroy the potentially harmful cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] All nucleated cells in the body (along with platelets) display class I major histocompatibility complex (MHC-I molecules).
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Antigens generated endogenously within these cells are bound to MHC-I molecules and presented on the cell surface.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] This antigen presentation pathway enables the immune system to detect transformed or infected cells displaying peptides from modified-self (mutated) or foreign proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] In the presentation process, these proteins are mainly degraded into small peptides by cytosolic proteases in the proteasome, but there are also other cytoplasmic proteolytic pathways.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Then, peptides are distributed to the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) via the action of heat shock proteins and the transporter associated with antigen processing (TAP) which translocates the cytosolic peptides into the ER lumen in an ATP-dependent transport mechanism.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] There are several ER chaperones involved in MHC-I assembly, such as calnexin, calreticulin, Erp57, protein disulfide isomerase (PDI), and tapasin.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Specifically, the complex of TAP, tapasin, MHS Class 1, ERp57, and calreticulin is called the peptide-loading complex (PLC).
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Peptides are loaded to MHC-I peptide binding groove between two alpha helices at the bottom of the α1 and α2 domains of the MHC class I molecule.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] After releasing from tapasin, peptide-MHC-I complexes (pMHC-I) exit the ER and are transported to the cell surface by exocytic vesicles.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Naïve anti-viral T cells (CD8+) cannot directly eliminate transformed or infected cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] They have to be activated by the pMHC-I complexes of antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Here, antigen can be presented directly (as described above) or indirectly (cross-presentation) from virus-infected and non-infected cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] After the interaction between pMHC-I and TCR, in presence of co-stimulatory signals and/or cytokines, T cells are activated, migrate to the peripheral tissues and kill the target cells (infected or damaged cells) by inducing cytotoxicity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Cross-presentation is a special case in which MHC-I molecules are able to present extracellular antigens, usually displayed only by MHC-II molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] This ability appears in several APCs, mainly plasmacytoid dendritic cells in tissues that stimulate CD8+ T cells directly.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] This process is essential when APCs are not directly infected, triggering local antiviral and anti-tumor immune responses immediately without trafficking the APCs in the local lymph nodes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Antigens from the extracellular space and sometimes also endogenous ones are enclosed into endocytic vesicles and presented on the cell surface by MHC-II molecules to helper T cells expressing CD4.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Only APCs such as dendritic cells, B cells or macrophages express MHC-II molecules on their surface in substantial quantity, so expression of MHC-II molecules is more cell-specific than MHC-I.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] APCs usually internalise exogenous antigens by endocytosis, but also by pinocytosis, macroautophagy, endosomal microautophagy, or chaperone-mediated autophagy.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] In the first case, after internalisation, the antigens are enclosed in vesicles called endosomes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] There are three compartments involved in this antigen presentation pathway: early endosomes, late endosomes or endolysosomes, and lysosomes, where antigens are hydrolized by lysosome-associated enzymes (acid-dependent hydrolases, glycosidases, proteases, lipases).
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] This process is favored by gradual reduction of the pH.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] The main proteases in endosomes are cathepsins and the result is the degradation of the antigens into oligopeptides.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] MHC-II molecules are transported from the ER to the MHC class II loading compartment together with the protein invariant chain (Ii, CD74).
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] A non classical MHC-II molecule (HLA-DO and HLA-DM) catalyses the exchange of part of the CD74 (CLIP peptide) with the peptide antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Peptide-MHC-II complexes (pMHC-II) are transported to the plasma membrane and the processed antigen is presented to the helper T cells in the lymph nodes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] APCs undergo a process of maturation while migrating, via chemotactic signals, to lymphoid tissues, in which they lose the phagocytic capacity and develop an increased ability to communicate with T-cells by antigen-presentation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] As well as in CD8+ cytotoxic T cells, APCs need pMHC-II and additional costimulatory signals to fully activate naive T helper cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Alternative pathway of endogenous antigen processing and presentation over MHC-II molecules exists in medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTEC) via the process of autophagy.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] It is important for the process of central tolerance of T cells in particular the negative selection of autoreactive clones.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Random gene expression of the whole genome is achieved via the action of AIRE and a self-digestion of the expressed molecules presented on both MHC-I and MHC-II molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] B-cell receptors on the surface of B cells bind to intact native and undigested antigens of a structural nature, rather than to a linear sequence of a peptide which has been digested into small fragments and presented by MHC molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Large complexes of intact antigen are presented in lymph nodes to B cells by follicular dendritic cells in the form of immune complexes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/antigen-presentation] Some APCs expressing comparatively lower levels of lysosomal enzymes are thus less likely to digest the antigen they have captured before presenting it to B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cells, unlike the other two classes of lymphocytes, T cells and natural killer cells, express B cell receptors (BCRs) on their cell membrane.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] BCRs allow the B cell to bind to a foreign antigen, against which it will initiate an antibody response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cell receptors are extremely specific, with all BCRs on a B cell recognizing the same epitope.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cells develop from hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) that originate from bone marrow.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] HSCs first differentiate into multipotent progenitor (MPP) cells, then common lymphoid progenitor (CLP) cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] From here, their development into B cells occurs in several stages (shown in image to the right), each marked by various gene expression patterns and immunoglobulin H chain and L chain gene loci arrangements, the latter due to B cells undergoing V(D)J recombination as they develop.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cells undergo two types of selection while developing in the bone marrow to ensure proper development, both involving B cell receptors (BCR) on the surface of the cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Positive selection occurs through antigen-independent signalling involving both the pre-BCR and the BCR.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] If these receptors do not bind to their ligand, B cells do not receive the proper signals and cease to develop.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Negative selection occurs through the binding of self-antigen with the BCR; if the BCR can bind strongly to self-antigen, then the B cell undergoes one of four fates: clonal deletion, receptor editing, anergy, or ignorance (B cell ignores signal and continues development).
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] This negative selection process leads to a state of central tolerance, in which the mature B cells do not bind self antigens present in the bone marrow.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] To complete development, immature B cells migrate from the bone marrow into the spleen as transitional B cells, passing through two transitional stages: T1 and T2.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Throughout their migration to the spleen and after spleen entry, they are considered T1 B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Within the spleen, T1 B cells transition to T2 B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] T2 B cells differentiate into either follicular (FO) B cells or marginal zone (MZ) B cells depending on signals received through the BCR and other receptors.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Once differentiated, they are now considered mature B cells, or naïve B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cell activation occurs in the secondary lymphoid organs (SLOs), such as the spleen and lymph nodes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] After B cells mature in the bone marrow, they migrate through the blood to SLOs, which receive a constant supply of antigen through circulating lymph.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] At the SLO, B cell activation begins when the B cell binds to an antigen via its BCR.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Although the events taking place immediately after activation have yet to be completely determined, it is believed that B cells are activated in accordance with the kinetic segregation model , initially determined in T lymphocytes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] This model denotes that before antigen stimulation, receptors diffuse through the membrane coming into contact with Lck and CD45 in equal frequency, rendering a net equilibrium of phosphorylation and non-phosphorylation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] It is only when the cell comes in contact with an antigen presenting cell that the larger CD45 is displaced due to the close distance between the two membranes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] This allows for net phosphorylation of the BCR and the initiation of the signal transduction pathway.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Of the three B cell subsets, FO B cells preferentially undergo T cell-dependent activation while MZ B cells and B1 B cells preferentially undergo T cell-independent activation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cell activation is enhanced through the activity of CD21, a surface receptor in complex with surface proteins CD19 and CD81 (all three are collectively known as the B cell coreceptor complex).
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] When a BCR binds an antigen tagged with a fragment of the C3 complement protein, CD21 binds the C3 fragment, co-ligates with the bound BCR, and signals are transduced through CD19 and CD81 to lower the activation threshold of the cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Antigens that activate B cells with the help of T-cell are known as T cell-dependent (TD) antigens and include foreign proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] They are named as such because they are unable to induce a humoral response in organisms that lack T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cell responses to these antigens takes multiple days, though antibodies generated have a higher affinity and are more functionally versatile than those generated from T cell-independent activation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Once a BCR binds a TD antigen, the antigen is taken up into the B cell through receptor-mediated endocytosis, degraded, and presented to T cells as peptide pieces in complex with MHC-II molecules on the cell membrane.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] T helper (TH) cells, typically follicular T helper (TFH) cells recognize and bind these MHC-II-peptide complexes through their T cell receptor (TCR).
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Following TCR-MHC-II-peptide binding, T cells express the surface protein CD40L as well as cytokines such as IL-4 and IL-21.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] CD40L serves as a necessary co-stimulatory factor for B cell activation by binding the B cell surface receptor CD40, which promotes B cell proliferation, immunoglobulin class switching, and somatic hypermutation as well as sustains T cell growth and differentiation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] T cell-derived cytokines bound by B cell cytokine receptors also promote B cell proliferation, immunoglobulin class switching, and somatic hypermutation as well as guide differentiation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] After B cells receive these signals, they are considered activated.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Once activated, B cells participate in a two-step differentiation process that yields both short-lived plasmablasts for immediate protection and long-lived plasma cells and memory B cells for persistent protection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] The first step, known as the extrafollicular response, occurs outside lymphoid follicles but still in the SLO.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] During this step activated B cells proliferate, may undergo immunoglobulin class switching, and differentiate into plasmablasts that produce early, weak antibodies mostly of class IgM.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] The second step consists of activated B cells entering a lymphoid follicle and forming a germinal center (GC), which is a specialized microenvironment where B cells undergo extensive proliferation, immunoglobulin class switching, and affinity maturation directed by somatic hypermutation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] These processes are facilitated by TFH and follicular dendritic cells within the GC and generate both high-affinity memory B cells and long-lived plasma cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Resultant plasma cells secrete large numbers of antibodies and either stay within the SLO or, more preferentially, migrate to bone marrow.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Antigens that activate B cells without T cell help are known as T cell-independent (TI) antigens and include foreign polysaccharides and unmethylated CpG DNA.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] They are named as such because they are able to induce a humoral response in organisms that lack T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cell response to these antigens is rapid, though antibodies generated tend to have lower affinity and are less functionally versatile than those generated from T cell-dependent activation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Memory B cell activation begins with the detection and binding of their target antigen, which is shared by their parent B cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Some memory B cells can be activated without T cell help, such as certain virus-specific memory B cells, but others need T cell help.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Upon antigen binding, the memory B cell takes up the antigen through receptor-mediated endocytosis, degrades it, and presents it to T cells as peptide pieces in complex with MHC-II molecules on the cell membrane.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Memory T helper (TH) cells, typically memory follicular T helper (TFH) cells, that were derived from T cells activated with the same antigen recognize and bind these MHC-II-peptide complexes through their TCR.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] It is unclear whether the memory B cells undergo further affinity maturation within these secondary GCs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] *In vitro* activation of memory B cells can be achieved through stimulation with various activators, such as pokeweed mitogen or anti-CD40 monoclonal antibodies, however, a study found a combination of R-848 and recombinant human IL-2 to be the most efficient activator.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] A short-lived, proliferating antibody-secreting cell arising from B cell differentiation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Plasmablasts are generated early in an infection and their antibodies tend to have a weaker affinity towards their target antigen compared to plasma cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Plasmablasts can result from T cell-independent activation of B cells or the extrafollicular response from T cell-dependent activation of B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] A long-lived, non-proliferating antibody-secreting cell arising from B cell differentiation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] There is evidence that B cells first differentiate into a plasmablast-like cell, then differentiate into a plasma cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Plasma cells are generated later in an infection and, compared to plasmablasts, have antibodies with a higher affinity towards their target antigen due to affinity maturation in the germinal center (GC) and produce more antibodies.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Plasma cells typically result from the germinal center reaction from T cell-dependent activation of B cells, though they can also result from T cell-independent activation of B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] A cell with a mixture of B lymphocyte and plasma cell morphological features that is thought to be closely related to or a subtype of plasma cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Dormant B cell arising from B cell differentiation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Memory B cells can be generated from T cell-dependent activation through both the extrafollicular response and the germinal center reaction as well as from T cell-independent activation of B1 cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Most common type of B cell and, when not circulating through the blood, is found mainly in the lymphoid follicles of secondary lymphoid organs (SLOs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] They are responsible for generating the majority of high-affinity antibodies during an infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Found mainly in the marginal zone of the spleen and serves as a first line of defense against blood-borne pathogens, as the marginal zone receives large amounts of blood from the general circulation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] They can undergo both T cell-independent and T cell-dependent activation, but preferentially undergo T cell-independent activation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Arises from a developmental pathway different from FO B cells and MZ B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] (antibodies produced without infection), defend against mucosal pathogens, and primarily exhibit T cell-independent activation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] A true homologue of mouse B-1 cells has not been discovered in humans, though various cell populations similar to B-1 cells have been described.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] B cell type that stops the expansion of pathogenic, pro-inflammatory lymphocytes through the secretion of IL-10, IL-35, and TGF-β.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] by directly interacting with T cells to skew their differentiation towards Tregs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] No common Breg cell identity has been described and many Breg cell subsets sharing regulatory functions have been found in both mice and humans.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] It is currently unknown if Breg cell subsets are developmentally linked and how exactly differentiation into a Breg cell occurs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] There is evidence showing that nearly all B cell types can differentiate into a Breg cell through mechanisms involving inflammatory signals and BCR recognition.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Autoimmune disease can result from abnormal B cell recognition of self-antigens followed by the production of autoantibodies.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Autoimmune diseases where disease activity is correlated with B cell activity include scleroderma, multiple sclerosis, systemic lupus erythematosus, type 1 diabetes, post-infectious IBS, and rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Abnormal B cells may be relatively large and some diseases include this in their names, such as diffuse large B-cell lymphomas (DLBCLs) and intravascular large B-cell lymphoma.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Patients with B cell alymphocytosis are predisposed to infections.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] A study that investigated the methylome of B cells along their differentiation cycle, using whole-genome bisulfite sequencing (WGBS), showed that there is a hypomethylation from the earliest stages to the most differentiated stages.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] The largest methylation difference is between the stages of germinal center B cells and memory B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/b-cell] Furthermore, this study showed that there is a similarity between B cell tumors and long-lived B cells in their DNA methylation signatures.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In immunology, **clonal selection theory** explains the functions of cells of the immune system (lymphocytes) in response to specific antigens invading the body.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] The concept was introduced by Australian doctor Frank Macfarlane Burnet in 1957, in an attempt to explain the great diversity of antibodies formed during initiation of the immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] The theory has become the widely accepted model for how the human immune system responds to infection and how certain types of B and T lymphocytes are selected for destruction of specific antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] The theory states that in a pre-existing group of lymphocytes (both B and T cells), a specific antigen activates (i.e. selects) only its counter-specific cell, which then induces that particular cell to multiply, producing identical clones for antibody production.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] This activation occurs in secondary lymphoid organs such as the spleen and the lymph nodes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In short, the theory is an explanation of the mechanism for the generation of diversity of antibody specificity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] The first experimental evidence came in 1958, when Gustav Nossal and Joshua Lederberg showed that one B cell always produces only one antibody.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] The idea turned out to be the foundation of molecular immunology, especially in adaptive immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In 1900, Paul Ehrlich proposed the so-called "side chain theory" of antibody production.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] According to it, certain cells exhibit on their surface different "side chains" (i.e. membrane-bound antibodies) able to react with different antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] When an antigen is present, it binds to a matching side chain.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Then the cell stops producing all other side chains and starts intensive synthesis and secretion of the antigen-binding side chain as a soluble antibody.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Though distinct from clonal selection, Ehrlich's idea was a selection theory far more accurate than the instructive theories that dominated immunology in the next decades.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In 1955, Danish immunologist Niels Jerne put forward a hypothesis that there is already a vast array of soluble antibodies in the serum prior to any infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] The entrance of an antigen into the body results in the selection of only one type of antibody to match it.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] This supposedly occurred by certain cells phagocytosing the immune complexes and somehow replicating the antibody structure to produce more of it.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Talmage hypothesized that antigens bind to antibodies on the surface of antibody-producing cells and "only those cells are selected for multiplication whose synthesized product has affinity for the antigen".
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] The key difference from Ehrlich's theory was that every cell was presumed to synthesize only one sort of antibody.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] After antigen binding the cell proliferates, forming clones with identical antibodies.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Later in 1957, Australian immunologist Frank Macfarlane Burnet published a paper titled "A modification of Jerne's theory of antibody production using the concept of clonal selection" in the rather obscure *Australian Journal of Science*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In it Burnet expanded the ideas of Talmage and named the resulting theory the "clonal selection theory".
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] He further formalised the theory in his 1959 book *The Clonal Selection Theory of Acquired Immunity*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] He explained immunological memory as the cloning of two types of lymphocyte.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] One clone acts immediately to combat infection whilst the other is longer lasting, remaining in the immune system for a long time and causing immunity to that antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] According to Burnet's hypothesis, among antibodies are molecules that can probably correspond with varying degrees of precision to all, or virtually all, the antigenic determinants that occur in biological material other than those characteristic of the body itself.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Each type of pattern is a specific product of a clone of lymphocytes and it is the essence of the hypothesis that each cell automatically has available on its surface representative reactive sites equivalent to those of the globulin they produce.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] When an antigen enters the blood or tissue fluids it is assumed that it will attach to the surface of any lymphocyte carrying reactive sites that correspond to one of its antigenic determinants.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Then the cell is activated and undergoes proliferation to produce a variety of descendants.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In this way, preferential proliferation is initiated of all those clones whose reactive sites correspond to the antigenic determinants on the antigens present in the body.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] The descendants are capable of active liberation of soluble antibody and lymphocytes, the same functions as the parental forms.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In 1958, Gustav Nossal and Joshua Lederberg showed that one B cell always produces only one antibody, which was the first direct evidence supporting the clonal selection theory.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Burnet and Peter Medawar worked together on understanding immunological tolerance, a phenomenon also explained by clonal selection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] This is the organism's ability to tolerate the introduction of cells prior to the development of an immune response as long as it occurs early in the organism's development.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] There are a vast number of lymphocytes occurring in the immune system, ranging from cells that tolerate self tissue to cells that do not.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] However, only cells tolerant of self tissue survive the embryonic stage.If non-self tissue is introduced, lymphocytes that develop are the ones that include the non-self tissues as self tissue.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In 1959, Burnet proposed that under certain circumstances, tissues could be successfully transplanted into foreign recipients.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] This work has led to a much greater understanding of the immune system and also great advances in tissue transplantation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Burnet and Medawar shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1960.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] In 1974, Niels Kaj Jerne proposed that the immune system functions as a network that is regulated via interactions between the variable parts of lymphocytes and their secreted molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Immune network theory is firmly based on the concept of clonal selection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/clonal-selection] Jerne won the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1984, largely for his contributions to immune network theory.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] After the inflammatory immune response to danger-associated antigen, some of the antigen-specific T cells and B cells persist in the body and become long-living memory T and B cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] After a second encounter with the same antigen, they recognize the antigen and mount a faster and more robust response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immunological memory is the basis of vaccination.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Emerging resources show that even the innate immune system can initiate a more efficient immune response and pathogen elimination after the previous stimulation with a pathogen, respectively with pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) or damage-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Innate immune memory (also called trained immunity) is neither antigen-specific nor dependent on gene rearrangement; the different response is caused by changes in epigenetic programming and shifts in immunometabolism.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Innate immune memory has been observed in invertebrates and vertebrates.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immune memory can be lost if the corresponding memory cells die out ("immune amnesia").
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] For example, previously acquired immune memory can be depleted by measles in unvaccinated children, leaving them at risk of infection by other pathogens in the years after infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] This weakening of the immune system increases the risk of death from other diseases.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immunological memory occurs after a primary immune response against the antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immunological memory is thus created by each individual after a previous initial exposure to a potentially dangerous agent.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The course of secondary immune response is similar to the primary immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] After the memory B cell recognizes the antigen, it presents the peptide in the MHC class II complex to nearby effector T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] That leads to activation of these cells and rapid proliferation of cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] After the primary immune response has disappeared, the effector cells of the immune response are eliminated.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] However, antibodies that were previously produced in the body persist and represent the humoral component of immunological memory and serve as an important defense against subsequent infections.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] In addition to the formed antibodies in the body, there remains a small number of memory T and B cells that make up the cellular component of the immunological memory.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] They stay in blood circulation in a resting state, and at the subsequent encounter with the same antigen, these cells are able to respond immediately and eliminate the antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Memory cells have a long life and last up to several decades in the body.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immunity to chickenpox, measles, and some other diseases lasts a lifetime.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immunity to many diseases eventually wears off.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The immune system's response to a few diseases, such as dengue, counterproductively worsens the next infection (antibody-dependent enhancement).
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] As of 2019, researchers are still trying to find out why some vaccines produce lifelong immunity, while the effectiveness of other vaccines drops to zero in less than 30 years (for mumps) or less than six months (for H3N2 influenza).
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Memory B cells are plasma cells that are able to produce antibodies for a long time.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Unlike the naive B cells involved in the primary immune response, the memory B cell response is slightly different.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The memory B cell has already undergone clonal expansion, differentiation and affinity maturation, so it is able to divide multiple times faster and produce antibodies with much higher affinity (especially IgG).
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] In contrast, the naive plasma cell is fully differentiated and cannot be further stimulated by antigen to divide or increase antibody production.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Memory B cell activity in secondary lymphatic organs is highest during the first 2 weeks after infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Subsequently, after 2 to 4 weeks, its response declines.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] After the germinal center reaction, the memory plasma cells are located in the bone marrow, which is the main site of antibody production within the immunological memory.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Memory T cells can be both CD4+ and CD8+.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] These memory T cells do not require further antigen stimulation to proliferate; therefore, they do not need a signal via MHC.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Memory T cells can be divided into two functionally distinct groups based on the expression of the CCR7 chemokine receptor.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] This chemokine indicates the direction of migration into secondary lymphatic organs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Those memory T cells that do not express CCR7 (these are CCR7-) have receptors to migrate to the site of inflammation in the tissue and represent an immediate effector cell population.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] These cells were named memory effector T cells (TEM).
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] After repeated stimulation they produce large amounts of IFN-γ, IL-4 and IL-5.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] In contrast, CCR7+ memory T cells lack proinflammatory and cytotoxic functions but express receptors for lymph node migration.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] These cells were named central memory T cells (TCM).
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] They effectively stimulate dendritic cells, and after repeated stimulation, they are able to differentiate into CCR7- effector memory T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Both populations of these memory cells originate from naive T cells and remain in the body for several years after initial immunization.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Experimental techniques used to study these cells include measuring antigen-stimulated cell proliferation and cytokine release, staining with peptide-MHC multimers, or using an activation-induced marker (AIM) assay.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Many invertebrates such as species of freshwater snails, copepod crustaceans, and tapeworms have been observed activating innate immune memory to instigate a more efficient immune response to second encounter with specific pathogens, despite missing an adaptive branch of the immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] *RAG1*-deficient mice without functional T and B cells were able to survive the administration of a lethal dose of *Candida albicans* when exposed previously to a much smaller amount, showing that vertebrates also retain this ability.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Despite not having the ability to manufacture antibodies like the adaptive immune system, the innate immune system has immune memory properties as well.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Innate immune memory—trained immunity—is defined as a long-term functional reprogramming of innate immune cells evoked by exogenous or endogenous insults and leading to an altered response towards a second challenge after returning to a non-activated state.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] When innate immune cells receive an activation signal, for example, through recognition of PAMPs with pattern recognition receptors (PRRs), they start the expression of proinflammatory genes, initiate an inflammatory response, and undergo epigenetic reprogramming.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] After the second stimulation, the transcription activation is faster and more robust.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immunological memory was reported in monocytes, macrophages, natural killer cells, and innate lymphoid cells 1, 2, and 3 cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Concomitantly, some nonimmune cells, for example, epithelial stem cells on barrier tissues, or fibroblasts, change their epigenetic state and respond differently after priming insult.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] At the steady state, unstimulated cells have reduced biosynthetic activities and more condensed chromatin with reduced gene transcription.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The interaction of exogenous PAMPs (β-glucan, muramyl peptide) or endogenous DAMPs (oxidized LDL, uric acid) with PRR initiates a cellular response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Triggered Intracellular signaling cascades lead to the upregulation of metabolic pathways such as glycolysis, the Krebs cycle, and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] An increase in metabolic activity provides cells with energy and building blocks, which are needed for the production of signaling molecules such as cytokines and chemokines.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Signal transduction changes the epigenetic marks and increases chromatin accessibility, to allow binding of transcription factors and the start of transcription of genes connected with inflammation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] There is an interplay between metabolism and epigenetic changes because some metabolites such as fumarate and acetyl-CoA can activate or inhibit enzymes involved in chromatin remodeling.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] After the stimulus let up, there is no need for immune factors production, and their expression in immune cells is terminated.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Several epigenetic modifications created during stimulation remain.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Characteristic epigenetic rewiring in trained cells is the accumulation of H3K4me3 on immune gene promoters and the increase of H3K4me1 and H3K27ac on enhancers.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Additionally, cellular metabolism does not return to the state before stimulation, and trained cells remain in a prepared state.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] This status can last from weeks to several months and can be transmitted to daughter cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Secondary stimulation induces a new response, which is faster and stronger.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immune memory brings a major evolutionary advantage when the organism faces repeated infections.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Inflammation is very costly, and increased effectivity of response accelerates pathogen elimination and prevents damage to the host's own tissue.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Classical adaptive immune memory evolved in jawed vertebrates and in jawless fish (lamprey), which is approximately just 1% of living organisms.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Some form of immune memory is, therefore, reported in other species.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] In plants and invertebrates, faster kinetics, increased magnitude of immune response, and an improved survival rate can be seen after secondary infection encounters.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Immune memory is common for the vast majority of biodiversity on Earth.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] It has been proposed that immune memory in innate and adaptive immunity represents an evolutionary continuum in which a more robust immune response evolved first, mediated by epigenetic reprogramming.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] In contrast, specificity through antigen-specific receptors evolved later in some vertebrates.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Adaptive immune memory share many fundamental parts with innate immunity and are best viewed as an elaboration of the innate system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] For example, lymphoid cells can be identified in some pre-vertebrate deuterostomes (i.e., sea urchins).
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The adaptive immune system evolved exactly twice, once each in the two branches of vertebrates that diverged approximately 500 million years ago, the jawed fish and the jawless fish.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] In both systems the adaptive lymphocytes have a division of labor functionally analogous to the B/αβT/δγT split, suggesting that their non-adaptive common ancestor already had a similar division.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] A major event in the history of vertebrates is the two rounds of whole genomd duplication (2R).
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] There ended up being four copies of every part of the genome, making the loss and re-purposing of genes evolutionarily useful.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] One particular region, the *primordial immune complex*, gave rise to two paralogous regions of the human genome important to adaptive immunity: the Ig/TCR part of chromosome 14 and the MHC region of chromosome 9.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The 14/9 arrangement sets the stage for the adaptive system, but still lacks the ability to rearrange V(D)J exons.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] This ability was fortuitously gained when a RAG transposon containing the precursor to the recombination-activating genes invaded an immunoglobin and split its VJ exon into V and J.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Further transposon activity and duplication lead to the many copies of V, D and J that generate antibody variation today.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The above only explains how the system arose, not why it happened despite the high energy costs and the unknown gains.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] It can be also reasoned that an adaptive immune memory would be more useful to longer-lived organisms than otherwise, as it relies on the accumulation of information.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Furthermore, research models show that memory cell pools accrue diversity based on the number of individual pathogens exposed, even at the cost of efficiency when encountering more common pathogens: another possible cost to being adaptive.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] One theory is that the benefit could really be high: early vertebrates may be large predators that use the *K* stragtegy, that is to make a limited amount of offsprings and a higher investment in each of them.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] (Vertebrates such as cod, seahorses, and axolotl all have devolved AIS and were presumably not under much pathogen stress at some point in ther lineage.) Another theory is that vertebrates have so much more metabolic activity that the cost is insignificant.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The measles virus can deplete previously acquired immune memory by killing cells that make antibodies, thus weakening the immune system and increasing the risk of death from other diseases.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Suppression of the immune system by measles lasts about two years and has been epidemiologically implicated in up to 90% of childhood deaths in third world countries, and historically may have caused rather more deaths in the United States, the UK and Denmark than were directly caused by measles.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Although the measles vaccine contains an attenuated strain, it does not deplete immune memory.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Complications of measles are relatively common.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Some are caused directly by the virus, while others are caused by viral suppression of the immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] This phenomenon, known as "immune amnesia", increases the risk of secondary bacterial infections; two months after recovery there is an 11–73% decrease in the number of antibodies against other bacteria and viruses.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Population studies from prior to the introduction of the measles vaccine suggest that immune amnesia typically lasts 2–3 years.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Primate studies suggest that immune amnesia in measles is effected by replacement of memory lymphocytes with ones that are specific to measles virus, since they are destroyed after being infected by the virus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] This creates lasting immunity to measles re-infection, but decreases immunity to other pathogens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Complications may be directly related to the virus - e.g. viral pneumonia or viral laryngotracheobronchitis (croup) - or related to the damage measles virus causes to tissues and the immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] The most serious direct complications include acute encephalitis, corneal ulceration (leading to corneal scarring); and subacute sclerosing panencephalitis, a progressive and fatal inflammation of the brain that occurs in about 1 in 600 unvaccinated infants under 15 months.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Common secondary infections include infectious diarrhea, bacterial pneumonia, and otitis media.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Many autoimmune diseases involve the immunological memory improperly targeting a part of the body and could be resolved if the corresponding memory is lost.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] CAR T cells are genetically engineered T cells that can be designed to recognize any molecule as the target, so that they can be made to kill any type of cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] A heavy-handed approach that targets every CD19, which is found on every B cell, has received much press due its fast and impressive results in systemic lupus erythematosus nephritis.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] There have been than 100 clinicalical trials studying the use of CAR T to kill the B cells that cause autoimmunity; some targets all B cells, some only memory B cells, and a few aiming to only kill B cells that produce a specific autoantibody.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] A related technique is CAR Treg, where the regulatory type of T cells are used.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] Tregs do not kill cells and instead suppresses immune responses.
[src:adaptive-immunity/immunological-memory] CAR Treg cells can be designed to suppress the immune response around some organ targeted by autoimmunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The **major histocompatibility complex** (**MHC**) is a large locus on vertebrate DNA containing a set of closely linked polymorphic genes that code for cell surface proteins essential for the adaptive immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] These cell surface proteins are called **MHC molecules**.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Its name comes from its discovery during the study of transplanted tissue compatibility.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Later studies revealed that tissue rejection due to incompatibility is only a facet of the full function of MHC molecules, which is to bind an antigen derived from self-proteins, or from pathogens, and bring the antigen presentation to the cell surface for recognition by the appropriate T-cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC molecules mediate the interactions of leukocytes, also called white blood cells (WBCs), with other leukocytes or with body cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The MHC determines donor compatibility for organ transplant, as well as one's susceptibility to autoimmune diseases.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In a cell, protein molecules of the host's own phenotype or of other biologic entities are continually synthesized and degraded.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Each MHC molecule on the cell surface displays a small peptide (a molecular fraction of a protein) called an epitope.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The presented self-antigens prevent an organism's immune system from targeting its own cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The presentation of pathogen-derived proteins results in the elimination of the infected cell by the immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Sexual selection has been observed in male mice choosing to mate with females with different MHCs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Also, at least for MHC I presentation, there has been evidence of antigenic peptide splicing, which can combine peptides from different proteins, vastly increasing antigen diversity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The first descriptions of the MHC were made by British immunologist Peter Gorer in 1936.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC genes were first identified in inbred mice strains.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Clarence Little transplanted tumors across different strains and found rejection of transplanted tumors according to strains of host versus donor.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] George Snell selectively bred two mouse strains, attained a new strain nearly identical to one of the progenitor strains, but differing crucially in histocompatibility—that is, tissue compatibility upon transplantation—and thereupon identified an MHC locus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Later Jean Dausset demonstrated the existence of MHC genes in humans and described the first human leucocyte antigen, the protein which we call now HLA-A2.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Some years later Baruj Benacerraf showed that polymorphic MHC genes not only determine an individual's unique constitution of antigens but also regulate the interaction among the various cells of the immunological system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] These three scientists have been awarded the 1980 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries concerning "genetically determined structures on the cell surface that regulate immunological reactions".
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The first fully sequenced and annotated MHC was published for humans in 1999 by a consortium of sequencing centers from the UK, USA and Japan in *Nature*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] It was a "virtual MHC" since it was a mosaic from different individuals.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] A much shorter MHC locus from chickens was published in the same issue of *Nature*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Many other species have been sequenced and the evolution of the MHC was studied, e.g. in the gray short-tailed opossum (*Monodelphis domestica*), a marsupial, MHC spans 3.95 Mb, yielding 114 genes, 87 shared with humans.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Marsupial MHC genotypic variation lies between eutherian mammals and birds, taken as the minimal MHC encoding, but is closer in organization to that of nonmammals.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The IPD-MHC Database was created which provides a centralised repository for sequences of the Major Histocompatibility Complex (MHC) from a number of different species.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] As of the release on December 19, 2019, the database contains information on 77 species.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The MHC locus is present in all jawed vertebrates; it is assumed to have arisen about 450 million years ago.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Despite the difference in the number of genes included in the MHC of different species, the overall organization of the locus is rather similar.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Usual MHC contains about a hundred genes and pseudogenes, not all of which are involved in immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In humans, the MHC region occurs on chromosome 6, between the flanking genetic markers *MOG* and *COL11A2* (from 6p22.1 to 6p21.3 about 29Mb to 33Mb on the hg38 assembly), and contains 224 genes spanning 3.6 megabase pairs (3 600 000 bases).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The human MHC is also called the HLA (human leukocyte antigen) complex (often just the HLA).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Similarly, there is SLA (Swine leukocyte antigens), BoLA (Bovine leukocyte antigens), DLA for dogs, etc.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] However, historically, the MHC in mice is called the Histocompatibility system 2 or just the H-2, whereas it has been referred to as the RT1 complex in rats, and the B locus in chickens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The MHC gene family is divided into three subgroups: MHC class I, MHC class II, and MHC class III.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Among all those genes present in MHC, there are two types of genes coding for the proteins MHC class I molecules and MHC class II molecules that are directly involved in the antigen presentation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] These genes are highly polymorphic, 19031 alleles of class I HLA, and 7183 of class II HLA are deposited for human in the IMGT database.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC class I molecules are expressed in all nucleated cells and also in platelets—in essence all cells but red blood cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] It presents epitopes to killer T cells, also called cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] A CTL expresses CD8 receptors, in addition to T-cell receptors (TCRs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] When a CTL's CD8 receptor docks to a MHC class I molecule, if the CTL's TCR fits the epitope within the MHC class I molecule, the CTL triggers the cell to undergo programmed cell death by apoptosis.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Thus, MHC class I helps mediate cellular immunity, a primary means to address intracellular pathogens, such as viruses and some bacteria, including bacterial L forms, bacterial genus *Mycoplasma*, and bacterial genus *Rickettsia*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In humans, MHC class I comprises HLA-A, HLA-B, and HLA-C molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The first crystal structure of Class I MHC molecule, human HLA-A2, was published in 1989.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The structure revealed that MHC-I molecules are heterodimers.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] They have a polymorphic heavy α-subunit whose gene occurs inside the MHC locus and small invariant β2 microglobulin subunit whose gene is usually located outside of it.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Polymorphic heavy chain of MHC-I molecule contains N-terminal extra-cellular region composed by three domains, α1, α2, and α3, transmembrane helix to hold MHC-I molecule on the cell surface and short cytoplasmic tail.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Two domains, α1 and α2, form deep peptide-binding groove between two long α-helices and the floor of the groove formed by eight β-strands.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Immunoglobulin-like domain α3 involved in the interaction with CD8 co-receptor. β2 microglobulin provides stability of the complex and participates in the recognition of peptide-MHC class I complex by CD8 co-receptor.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The peptide is non-covalently bound to MHC-I, it is held by the several pockets on the floor of the peptide-binding groove.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Amino acid side-chains that are most polymorphic in human alleles fill the central and widest portion of the binding groove, while conserved side-chains are clustered at the narrower ends of the groove.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC class II can be conditionally expressed by all cell types, but normally occurs only on "professional" antigen-presenting cells (APCs): macrophages, B cells, and especially dendritic cells (DCs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] An APC takes up an antigenic protein, performs antigen processing, and returns a molecular fraction of it—a fraction termed the epitope—and displays it on the APC's surface coupled within an MHC class II molecule (antigen presentation).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] On the cell's surface, the epitope can be recognized by immunologic structures like T-cell receptors (TCRs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The molecular region which binds to the epitope is the paratope.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] On surfaces of helper T cells are CD4 receptors, as well as TCRs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] When a naive helper T cell's CD4 molecule docks to an APC's MHC class II molecule, its TCR can meet and bind the epitope coupled within the MHC class II.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC class II thus mediates immunization to—or, if APCs polarize Th0 cells principally to Treg cells, immune tolerance of—an antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The polarization during primary exposure to an antigen is key in determining a number of chronic diseases, such as inflammatory bowel diseases and asthma, by skewing the immune response that memory Th cells coordinate when their memory recall is triggered upon secondary exposure to similar antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] B cells express MHC class II to present antigens to Th0, but when their B cell receptors bind matching epitopes, interactions which are not mediated by MHC, these activated B cells secrete soluble immunoglobulins: antibody molecules mediating humoral immunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Class II MHC molecules are also heterodimers, genes for both α and β subunits are polymorphic and located within MHC class II subregion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The peptide-binding groove of MHC-II molecules is formed by the N-terminal domains of both subunits of the heterodimer, α1 and β1, unlike MHC-I molecules, where two domains of the same chain are involved.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In addition, both subunits of MHC-II contain transmembrane helix and immunoglobulin domains α2 or β2 that can be recognized by CD4 co-receptors.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In this way, MHC molecules guide the type of lymphocytes that may bind to the given antigen with high affinity, as different lymphocytes express different T-Cell Receptor (TCR) co-receptors.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC class II molecules in humans have five to six isotypes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] **Classical molecules** present peptides to CD4+ lymphocytes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] **Nonclassical molecules**, also known as accessories, have intracellular functions.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] They are not exposed on cell membranes, but are found in internal membranes, where they assist with the loading of antigenic peptides onto classic MHC class II molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The important nonclassical MHC class II molecule DM is only found from the evolutionary level of lungfish, although also in more primitive fishes both classical and nonclassical MHC class II are found.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Unlike classes I and II, Class III molecules have physiological roles and are encoded between classes I and II on the short arm of human chromosome 6.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Class III molecules include several secreted proteins with immune functions: components of the complement system (such as C2, C4, and B factor), cytokines (such as TNF-α, LTA, and LTB), and heat shock proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC is the tissue-antigen that allows the immune system (more specifically T cells) to bind to, recognize, and tolerate itself (autorecognition).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC is also the chaperone for intracellular peptides that are complexed with MHCs and presented to T cell receptors (TCRs) as potential foreign antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC interacts with TCR and its co-receptors to optimize binding conditions for the TCR-antigen interaction, in terms of antigen binding affinity and specificity, and signal transduction effectiveness.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Essentially, the MHC-peptide complex is a complex of auto-antigen/allo-antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Upon binding, T cells should in principle tolerate the auto-antigen, but activate when exposed to the allo-antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Disease states occur when this principle is disrupted.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Autoimmune reaction: The presence of certain MHC molecules can increase the risk of autoimmune diseases more than others.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] It is unclear how exactly having the HLA-B27 tissue type increases the risk of ankylosing spondylitis and other associated inflammatory diseases, but mechanisms involving aberrant antigen presentation or T cell activation have been hypothesized.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Tissue allorecognition: MHC molecules in complex with peptide epitopes are essentially ligands for TCRs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] T cells become activated by binding to the peptide-binding grooves of any MHC molecule that they were not trained to recognize during positive selection in the thymus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In their development in the thymus, T lymphocytes are selected to recognize the host's own MHC molecules, but not other self antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Following selection, each T lymphocyte shows dual specificity: The TCR recognizes self MHC, but only non-self antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC restriction occurs during lymphocyte development in the thymus through a process known as positive selection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] T cells that do not receive a positive survival signal — mediated mainly by thymic epithelial cells presenting self peptides bound to MHC molecules — to their TCR undergo apoptosis.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Positive selection ensures that mature T cells can functionally recognize MHC molecules in the periphery (i.e. elsewhere in the body).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The TCRs of T lymphocytes recognise only sequential epitopes, also called linear epitopes, of only peptides and only if coupled within an MHC molecule.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC molecules enable immune system surveillance of the population of protein molecules in a host cell, and greater MHC diversity permits greater diversity of antigen presentation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In 1976, Yamazaki *et al* demonstrated a sexual selection mate choice by male mice for females of a different MHC.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Similar results have been obtained with fish.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Some data find lower rates of early pregnancy loss in human couples of dissimilar MHC genes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC may be related to mate choice in some human populations, a theory that found support by studies by Ober and colleagues in 1997, as well as by Chaix and colleagues in 2008.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] However, the latter findings have been controversial.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] If it exists, the phenomenon might be mediated by olfaction, as MHC phenotype appears strongly involved in the strength and pleasantness of perceived odour of compounds from sweat.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Fatty acid esters—such as methyl undecanoate, methyl decanoate, methyl nonanoate, methyl octanoate, and methyl hexanoate—show strong connection to MHC.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In 2005 in a group of 58 subjects, women were more indecisive when presented with MHCs like their own, although with oral contraceptives, the women showed no particular preference.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] No studies show the extent to which odor preference determines mate selection (or vice versa).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Most mammals have MHC variants similar to those of humans, who bear great allelic diversity, especially among the nine classical genes—seemingly due largely to gene duplication—though human MHC regions have many pseudogenes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The most diverse loci, namely HLA-A, HLA-B, and HLA-C, have roughly 6000, 7200, and 5800 known alleles, respectively.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Many HLA alleles are ancient, sometimes of closer homology to a chimpanzee MHC alleles than to some other human alleles of the same gene.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC allelic diversity has challenged evolutionary biologists for explanation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Most posit balancing selection (see polymorphism (biology)), which is any natural selection process whereby no single allele is absolutely most fit, such as frequency-dependent selection and heterozygote advantage.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Pathogenic coevolution, as a type of balancing selection, posits that common alleles are under greatest pathogenic pressure, driving positive selection of uncommon alleles—moving targets, so to say, for pathogens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] As pathogenic pressure on the previously common alleles decreases, their frequency in the population stabilizes, and remain circulating in a large population.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Genetic drift is also a major driving force in some species.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] It is possible that the combined effects of some or all of these factors cause the genetic diversity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Beyond allelic polymorphism, the degree of evolutionary divergence between MHC alleles within individuals also influences immune function.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] More divergent allele pairs enable presentation of a broader and less redundant repertoire of peptides, thereby potentially enhancing immune recognition.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] This concept, sometimes referred to as MHC or HLA evolutionary divergence, extends classical models of MHC diversity and heterozygote advantage by treating allelic variation as a continuum rather than a binary state.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC diversity has also been suggested as a possible indicator for conservation, because large, stable populations tend to display greater MHC diversity than smaller, isolated populations.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Small, fragmented populations that have experienced a population bottleneck typically have lower MHC diversity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] For example, relatively low MHC diversity has been observed in the cheetah (*Acinonyx jubatus*), Eurasian beaver (*Castor fiber*), and giant panda (*Ailuropoda melanoleuca*).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In 2007 low MHC diversity was attributed a role in disease susceptibility in the Tasmanian devil (*Sarcophilus harrisii*), native to the isolated island of Tasmania, such that an antigen of a transmissible tumor, involved in devil facial tumour disease, appears to be recognized as a *self antigen*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] To offset inbreeding, efforts to sustain genetic diversity in populations of endangered species and of captive animals have been suggested.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In ray-finned fish like rainbow trout, allelic polymorphism in MHC class II is reminiscent of that in mammals and predominantly maps to the peptide binding groove.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] However, in MHC class I of many teleost fishes, the allelic polymorphism is much more extreme than in mammals in the sense that the sequence identity levels between alleles can be very low and the variation extends far beyond the peptide binding groove.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] It has been speculated that this type of MHC class I allelic variation contributes to allograft rejection, which may be especially important in fish to avoid grafting of cancer cells through their mucosal skin.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The MHC locus (6p21.3) has 3 other paralogous loci in the human genome, namely 19pl3.1, 9q33–q34, and 1q21–q25.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In a transplant procedure, as of an organ or stem cells, MHC molecules themselves act as antigens and can provoke immune response in the recipient, thus causing transplant rejection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC molecules were identified and named after their role in transplant rejection between mice of different strains, though it took over 20 years to clarify MHC's role in presenting peptide antigens to cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Each human cell expresses six MHC class I alleles (one HLA-A, -B, and -C allele from each parent) and six to eight MHC class II alleles (one HLA-DP and -DQ, and one or two HLA-DR from each parent, and combinations of these).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The MHC variation in the human population is high, at least 350 alleles for HLA-A genes, 620 alleles for HLA-B, 400 alleles for DR, and 90 alleles for DQ.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Any two individuals who are not identical twins, triplets, or higher order multiple births, will express differing MHC molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] All MHC molecules can mediate transplant rejection, but HLA-C and HLA-DP, showing low polymorphism, seem least important.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] When maturing in the thymus, T lymphocytes are selected for their TCR incapacity to recognize self antigens, yet T lymphocytes can react against the donor MHC's peptide-binding groove, the variable region of MHC holding the presented antigen's epitope for recognition by TCR, the matching paratope.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] T lymphocytes of the recipient take the incompatible peptide-binding groove as nonself antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In all of the above situations, immunity is directed at the transplanted organ, sustaining lesions.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] A cross-reaction test between potential donor cells and recipient serum seeks to detect presence of preformed anti-HLA antibodies in the potential recipient that recognize donor HLA molecules, so as to prevent hyperacute rejection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In normal circumstances, compatibility between HLA-A, -B, and -DR molecules is assessed.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The higher the number of incompatibilities, the lower the five-year survival rate.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Global databases of donor information enhance the search for compatible donors.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The involvement in allogeneic transplant rejection appears to be an ancient feature of MHC molecules, because also in fish associations between transplant rejections and (mis-)matching of MHC class I and MHC class II were observed.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Human MHC class I and II are also called human leukocyte antigen (HLA).
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] To clarify the usage, some of the biomedical literature uses HLA to refer specifically to the HLA protein molecules and reserves MHC for the region of the genome that encodes for this molecule, but this is not a consistent convention.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The most studied HLA genes are the nine classical MHC genes: *HLA-A, HLA-B, HLA-C, HLA-DPA1, HLA-DPB1, HLA-DQA1, HLA-DQB1, HLA-DRA*, and *HLA-DRB1*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In humans, the MHC gene cluster is divided into three regions: classes I, II, and III.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The A, B and C genes belong to MHC class I, whereas the six D genes belong to class II.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] MHC alleles are expressed in codominant fashion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The set of alleles that is present in each chromosome is called the MHC haplotype.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] In humans, each HLA allele is named with a number.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] For instance, for a given individual, his haplotype might be HLA-A2, HLA-B5, HLA-DR3, etc...
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Each heterozygous individual will have two MHC haplotypes, one each from the paternal and maternal chromosomes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The MHC genes are highly polymorphic; many different alleles exist in the different individuals inside a population.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The polymorphism is so high, in a mixed population (nonendogamic), no two individuals have exactly the same set of MHC molecules, with the exception of identical twins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The polymorphic regions in each allele are located in the region for peptide contact.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Of all the peptides that could be displayed by MHC, only a subset will bind strongly enough to any given HLA allele, so by carrying two alleles for each gene, each encoding specificity for unique antigens, a much larger set of peptides can be presented.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] On the other hand, inside a population, the presence of many different alleles ensures there will always be an individual with a specific MHC molecule able to load the correct peptide to recognize a specific microbe.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The evolution of the MHC polymorphism ensures that a population will not succumb to a new pathogen or a mutated one, because at least some individuals will be able to develop an adequate immune response to win over the pathogen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] The variations in the MHC molecules (responsible for the polymorphism) are the result of the inheritance of different MHC molecules, and they are not induced by recombination, as it is the case for the antigen receptors.
[src:adaptive-immunity/major-histocompatibility-complex] Because of the high levels of allelic diversity found within its genes, MHC has also attracted the attention of many evolutionary biologists, as well as disease specialists.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cells are born from hematopoietic stem cells, found in the bone marrow.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Developing T cells then migrate to the thymus gland to develop (or mature).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cells derive their name from the thymus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] After migration to the thymus, getting stimulated by thymosin, the precursor cells mature into several distinct types of T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cell differentiation also continues after they have left the thymus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Groups of specific, differentiated T cell subtypes have a variety of important functions in controlling and shaping the immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] One of these functions is immune-mediated cell death, and it is carried out by two major subtypes: CD8+ "killer" (cytotoxic, Effector tumor antigen-specific T cells) and CD4+ "helper" T cells, each respectively named for the presence of proteins CD8 or CD4 on the cell surface.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] CD8+ T cells, also known as "killer T cells," are cytotoxic, referring to their ability to directly kill virus-infected cells and cancer cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] CD8+ T cells are also able to use small signalling proteins, known as cytokines, to recruit other types of cells when mounting an immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] On the other hand, CD4+ T cells function as "helper cells." Unlike CD8+ killer T cells, the CD4+ helper T (TH) cells function by further activating memory B cells and cytotoxic T cells, which leads to a larger immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The specific adaptive immune response regulated by the TH cell depends on its subtype (i.e., T-helper1, T-helper2, T-helper17, and regulatory T-cell), which is distinguished by the types of cytokines they secrete.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] For this reason, these regulatory T cells have also been called "suppressor" T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These same regulatory T cells can also be co-opted by cancer cells to prevent the recognition of, and an immune response against, tumor cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] All T cells originate from c-kit+Sca1+ haematopoietic stem cells (HSC) that reside in the bone marrow.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] In some cases, the origin might be the foetal liver during embryonic development.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The HSC then differentiate into multipotent progenitors (MPP) which retain the potential to become both myeloid and lymphoid cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The process of differentiation then proceeds to a common lymphoid progenitor (CLP), which can only differentiate into T, B, or NK cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These CLP cells then migrate via the blood to the thymus, where they engraft:.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Henceforth they are known as thymocytes, the immature stage of a T cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The earliest cells which arrived in the thymus are commonly termed *double-negative*, as they express neither the CD4 nor CD8 co-receptor.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The newly arrived CLP cells are CD4−CD8−CD44+CD25−ckit+ cells, and are termed early thymic progenitor (ETP) cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These cells will then undergo a round of division and downregulate c-kit and are termed *double-negative one* (DN1) cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] To become T cells, the thymocytes must undergo multiple DN stages as well as positive selection and negative selection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Double negative thymocytes can be identified by the surface expression of CD2, CD5, and CD7.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Still during the double negative stages, CD34 expression stops and CD1 is expressed.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Expression of both CD4 and CD8 makes them *double positive*, and matures into either CD4+ or CD8+ cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] A critical step in T cell maturation is making a functional T cell receptor (TCR).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Each mature T cell will ultimately contain a unique TCR that reacts to a random pattern, allowing the immune system to recognize many different types of pathogens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This process is essential in developing immunity to threats that the immune system has not encountered before, since due to random variation there will always be at least one TCR to match any new pathogen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] A thymocyte can only become an active T cell when it survives the process of developing a functional TCR.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The TCR consists of two major components, the alpha and beta chains.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These both contain random elements designed to produce a wide variety of different TCRs, but due to this huge variety they must be tested to make sure they work at all.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] First, the thymocytes attempt to create a functional beta chain, testing it against a 'mock' alpha chain.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Then they attempt to create a functional alpha chain.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Once a working TCR has been produced, the cells then must test if their TCR will identify threats correctly, and to do this it is required to recognize the body's major histocompatibility complex (MHC) in a process known as positive selection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The thymocyte must also ensure that it does not react adversely to "self" antigens, called negative selection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] If both positive and negative selection are successful, the TCR becomes fully operational and the thymocyte becomes a T cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] At the DN2 stage (CD44+CD25+), cells upregulate the recombination genes RAG1 and RAG2 and re-arrange the TCRβ locus, combining V-D-J recombination and constant region genes in an attempt to create a functional TCRβ chain.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] As the developing thymocyte progresses through to the DN3 stage (CD44−CD25+), the thymocyte expresses an invariant α-chain called pre-Tα alongside the TCRβ gene.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] If the rearranged β-chain successfully pairs with the invariant α-chain, signals are produced which cease rearrangement of the β-chain (and silence the alternate allele).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Although these signals require the pre-TCR at the cell surface, they are independent of ligand binding to the pre-TCR.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] If the chains successfully pair a pre-TCR forms, and the cell downregulates CD25 and is termed a DN4 cell (CD25−CD44−).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These cells then undergo a round of proliferation, and begin to re-arrange the TCRα locus during the *double-positive* stage.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The process of positive selection takes 3 to 4 days and occurs in the thymic cortex.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Double-positive thymocytes (CD4+/CD8+) migrate deep into the thymic cortex, where they are presented with self-antigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These self-antigens are expressed by thymic cortical epithelial cells on MHC molecules, which reside on the surface of cortical epithelial cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Only thymocytes that interact well with MHC-I or MHC-II will receive a vital "survival signal", while those that cannot interact strongly enough will receive no signal and die from neglect.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This process ensures that the surviving thymocytes will have an 'MHC affinity' that means they will exhibit stronger binding affinity for specific MHC alleles in that organism.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The vast majority of developing thymocytes will not pass positive selection, and die during this process.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] A thymocyte's fate is determined during positive selection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Double-positive cells (CD4+/CD8+) that interact well with MHC *class II* molecules will eventually become CD4+ "helper" cells, whereas thymocytes that interact well with MHC *class I* molecules mature into CD8+ "killer" cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] A thymocyte becomes a CD4+ cell by down-regulating expression of its CD8 cell surface receptors.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] If the cell does not lose its signal, it will continue downregulating CD8 and become a CD4+, both CD8+ and CD4+ cells are now *single positive* cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This process does not filter for thymocytes that may cause autoimmunity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The potentially autoimmune cells are removed by the following process of negative selection, which occurs in the thymic medulla.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Negative selection removes thymocytes that are capable of strongly binding with "self" MHC molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Thymocytes that survive positive selection migrate towards the boundary of the cortex and medulla in the thymus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] While in the medulla, they are again presented with a self-antigen presented on the MHC complex of medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs). mTECs must be Autoimmune regulator positive (AIRE+) to properly express tissue-specific antigens on their MHC *class I* peptides.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Thymocytes that interact too strongly with the self-antigen receive an apoptotic signal that leads to cell death.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] However, some of these cells are selected to become Treg cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The remaining cells exit the thymus as mature naive T cells, also known as recent thymic emigrants.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This process is an important component of central tolerance and serves to prevent the formation of self-reactive T cells that are capable of inducing autoimmune diseases in the host.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] β-selection is the first checkpoint, where thymocytes that are able to form a functional pre-TCR (with an invariant alpha chain and a functional beta chain) are allowed to continue development in the thymus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Next, positive selection checks that thymocytes have successfully rearranged their TCRα locus and are capable of recognizing MHC molecules with appropriate affinity.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Negative selection in the medulla then eliminates thymocytes that bind too strongly to self-antigens expressed on MHC molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These selection processes allow for tolerance of self by the immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Typical naive T cells that leave the thymus (via the corticomedullary junction) are self-restricted, self-tolerant, and single positive.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] About 98% of thymocytes die during the development processes in the thymus by failing either positive selection or negative selection, whereas the other 2% survive and leave the thymus to become mature immunocompetent T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The thymus contributes fewer cells as a person ages.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] As the thymus shrinks by about 3% a year throughout middle age, a corresponding fall in the thymic production of naive T cells occurs, leaving peripheral T cell expansion and regeneration to play a greater role in protecting older people.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cells are grouped into a series of subsets based on their function.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] CD4 and CD8 T cells are selected in the thymus, but undergo further differentiation in the periphery to specialized cells which have different functions.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cell subsets were initially defined by function, but also have associated gene or protein expression patterns.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T helper cells (TH cells) assist other lymphocytes, including the maturation of B cells into plasma cells and memory B cells, and activation of cytotoxic T cells and macrophages.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These cells are also known as **CD4+ T cells** as they express the CD4 glycoprotein on their surfaces.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Helper T cells become activated when they are presented with peptide antigens by MHC class II molecules, which are expressed on the surface of antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Once activated, they divide rapidly and secrete cytokines that regulate or assist the immune response.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These cells can differentiate into one of several subtypes, which have different roles.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Cytokines direct T cells into particular subtypes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells (TC cells, CTLs, T-killer cells, killer T cells) destroy virus-infected cells and tumor cells, and are also implicated in transplant rejection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These cells are defined by the expression of the CD8 protein on their cell surface.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells recognize their targets by binding to short peptides (8-11 amino acids in length) associated with MHC class I molecules, present on the surface of all nucleated cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Cytotoxic T cells also produce the key cytokines IL-2 and IFNγ.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These cytokines influence the effector functions of other cells, in particular macrophages and NK cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Antigen-naive T cells expand and differentiate into memory and effector T cells after they encounter their cognate antigen within the context of an MHC molecule on the surface of a professional antigen presenting cell (e.g. a dendritic cell).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Appropriate co-stimulation must be present at the time of antigen encounter for this process to occur.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Historically, memory T cells were thought to belong to either the effector or central memory subtypes, each with their own distinguishing set of cell surface markers (see below).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Subsequently, numerous new populations of memory T cells were discovered including tissue-resident memory T (Trm) cells, stem memory TSCM cells, and virtual memory T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The single unifying theme for all memory T cell subtypes is that they are long-lived and can quickly expand to large numbers of effector T cells upon re-exposure to their cognate antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] By this mechanism they provide the immune system with "memory" against previously encountered pathogens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Memory T cells may be either CD4+ or CD8+ and usually express CD45RO.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Regulatory T cells are crucial for the maintenance of immune tolerance.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Their major role is to shut down T cell–mediated immunity toward the end of an immune reaction and to suppress autoreactive T cells that escaped the process of negative selection in the thymus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Two major classes of CD4+ Treg cells have been described—FOXP3+ Treg cells and FOXP3− Treg cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Regulatory T cells can develop either during normal development in the thymus, and are then known as thymic Treg cells, or can be induced peripherally and are called peripherally derived Treg cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These two subsets were previously called "naturally occurring" and "adaptive" (or "induced"), respectively.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Both subsets require the expression of the transcription factor FOXP3 which can be used to identify the cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Mutations of the *FOXP3* gene can prevent regulatory T cell development, causing the fatal autoimmune disease IPEX.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Several other types of T cells have suppressive activity, but do not express FOXP3 constitutively.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These include Tr1 and Th3 cells, which are thought to originate during an immune response and act by producing suppressive molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Tr1 cells are associated with IL-10, and Th3 cells are associated with TGF-beta.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Recently, Th17 cells have been added to this list.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Natural killer T cells (NKT cells – not to be confused with natural killer cells of the innate immune system) bridge the adaptive immune system with the innate immune system.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Unlike conventional T cells that recognize protein peptide antigens presented by major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules, NKT cells recognize glycolipid antigens presented by CD1d.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Once activated, these cells can perform functions ascribed to both helper and cytotoxic T cells: cytokine production and release of cytolytic/cell killing molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] They are also able to recognize and eliminate some tumor cells and cells infected with herpes viruses.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Mucosal associated invariant T (MAIT) cells display innate, effector-like qualities.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] In humans, MAIT cells are found in the blood, liver, lungs, and mucosa, defending against microbial activity and infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The MHC class I-like protein, MR1, is responsible for presenting bacterially-produced vitamin B metabolites to MAIT cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] After the presentation of foreign antigen by MR1, MAIT cells secrete pro-inflammatory cytokines and are capable of lysing bacterially-infected cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] MAIT cells can also be activated through MR1-independent signaling.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] In addition to possessing innate-like functions, this T cell subset supports the adaptive immune response and has a memory-like phenotype.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Furthermore, MAIT cells are thought to play a role in autoimmune diseases, such as multiple sclerosis, arthritis and inflammatory bowel disease, although definitive evidence is yet to be published.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) represent a small subset of T cells which possess a γδ TCR rather than the αβ TCR on the cell surface.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The majority of T cells express αβ TCR chains.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This group of T cells is much less common in humans and mice (about 2% of total T cells) and are found mostly in the gut mucosa, within a population of intraepithelial lymphocytes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] In rabbits, sheep, and chickens, the number of γδ T cells can be as high as 60% of total T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The antigenic molecules that activate γδ T cells are still mostly unknown.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] However, γδ T cells are not MHC-restricted and seem to be able to recognize whole proteins rather than requiring peptides to be presented by MHC molecules on APCs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Some murine γδ T cells recognize MHC class IB molecules.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Human γδ T cells that use the Vγ9 and Vδ2 gene fragments constitute the major γδ T cell population in peripheral blood.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These cells are unique in that they specifically and rapidly respond to a set of nonpeptidic phosphorylated isoprenoid precursors, collectively named phosphoantigens, which are produced by virtually all living cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The most common phosphoantigens from animal and human cells (including cancer cells) are isopentenyl pyrophosphate (IPP) and its isomer dimethylallyl pyrophosphate (DMPP).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Many microbes produce the active compound hydroxy-DMAPP (HMB-PP) and corresponding mononucleotide conjugates, in addition to IPP and DMAPP.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Plant cells produce both types of phosphoantigens.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Drugs activating human Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells comprise synthetic phosphoantigens and aminobisphosphonates, which upregulate endogenous IPP/DMAPP.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Activation of CD4+ T cells occurs through the simultaneous engagement of the T-cell receptor and a co-stimulatory molecule (like CD28, or ICOS) on the T cell by the major histocompatibility complex (MHCII) peptide and co-stimulatory molecules on the APC.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Both are required for production of an effective immune response; in the absence of co-stimulation, T cell receptor signalling alone results in anergy.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The signalling pathways downstream from co-stimulatory molecules usually engages the PI3K pathway generating PIP3 at the plasma membrane and recruiting PH domain containing signaling molecules like PDK1 that are essential for the activation of PKC-θ, and eventual IL-2 production.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Optimal CD8+ T cell response relies on CD4+ signalling.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] CD4+ cells are useful in the initial antigenic activation of naive CD8 T cells, and sustaining memory CD8+ T cells in the aftermath of an acute infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Therefore, activation of CD4+ T cells can be beneficial to the action of CD8+ T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The first signal is provided by binding of the T cell receptor to its cognate peptide presented on MHCII on an APC.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] MHCII is restricted to so-called professional antigen-presenting cells, like dendritic cells, B cells, and macrophages, to name a few.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The peptides presented to CD8+ T cells by MHC class I molecules are 8–13 amino acids in length; the peptides presented to CD4+ cells by MHC class II molecules are longer, usually 12–25 amino acids in length, as the ends of the binding cleft of the MHC class II molecule are open.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The second signal comes from co-stimulation, in which surface receptors on the APC are induced by a relatively small number of stimuli, usually products of pathogens, but sometimes breakdown products of cells, such as necrotic-bodies or heat shock proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The only co-stimulatory receptor expressed constitutively by naive T cells is CD28, so co-stimulation for these cells comes from the CD80 and CD86 proteins, which together constitute the B7 protein, (B7.1 and B7.2, respectively) on the APC.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Other receptors are expressed upon activation of the T cell, such as OX40 and ICOS, but these largely depend upon CD28 for their expression.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The second signal licenses the T cell to respond to an antigen.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Without it, the T cell becomes anergic, and it becomes more difficult for it to activate in future.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This mechanism prevents inappropriate responses to self, as self-peptides will not usually be presented with suitable co-stimulation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Once a T cell has been appropriately activated (i.e. has received signal one and signal two) it alters its cell surface expression of a variety of proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Markers of T cell activation include CD69, CD71 and CD25 (also a marker for Treg cells), and HLA-DR (a marker of human T cell activation).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] CTLA-4 expression is also up-regulated on activated T cells, which in turn outcompetes CD28 for binding to the B7 proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This is a checkpoint mechanism to prevent over activation of the T cell.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Activated T cells also change their cell surface glycosylation profile.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The T cell receptor exists as a complex of several proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The actual T cell receptor is composed of two separate peptide chains, which are produced from the independent T cell receptor alpha and beta (*TCRα* and *TCRβ*) genes.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The other proteins in the complex are the CD3 proteins: CD3εγ and CD3εδ heterodimers and, most important, a CD3ζ homodimer, which has a total of six ITAM motifs.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The ITAM motifs on the CD3ζ can be phosphorylated by Lck and in turn recruit ZAP-70.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Lck and/or ZAP-70 can also phosphorylate the tyrosines on many other molecules, not least CD28, LAT and SLP-76, which allows the aggregation of signalling complexes around these proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Phosphorylated LAT recruits SLP-76 to the membrane, where it can then bring in PLC-γ, VAV1, Itk and potentially PI3K.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] PLC-γ cleaves PI(4,5)P2 on the inner leaflet of the membrane to create the active intermediaries diacylglycerol (DAG), inositol-1,4,5-trisphosphate (IP3); PI3K also acts on PIP2, phosphorylating it to produce phosphatidlyinositol-3,4,5-trisphosphate (PIP3).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Most important in T cells is PKC-θ, critical for activating the transcription factors NF-κB and AP-1.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] IP3 is released from the membrane by PLC-γ and diffuses rapidly to activate calcium channel receptors on the ER, which induces the release of calcium into the cytosol.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Low calcium in the endoplasmic reticulum causes STIM1 clustering on the ER membrane and leads to activation of cell membrane CRAC channels that allows additional calcium to flow into the cytosol from the extracellular space.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This aggregated cytosolic calcium binds calmodulin, which can then activate calcineurin.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Calcineurin, in turn, activates NFAT, which then translocates to the nucleus.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] NFAT is a transcription factor that activates the transcription of a pleiotropic set of genes, most notable, IL-2, a cytokine that promotes long-term proliferation of activated T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] PLC-γ can also initiate the NF-κB pathway.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] DAG activates PKC-θ, which then phosphorylates CARMA1, causing it to unfold and function as a scaffold.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The cytosolic domains bind an adapter BCL10 via CARD (Caspase activation and recruitment domains) domains; that then binds TRAF6, which is ubiquitinated at K63.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This form of ubiquitination does not lead to degradation of target proteins.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Rather, it serves to recruit NEMO, IKKα and -β, and TAB1-2/ TAK1.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] TAK 1 phosphorylates IKK-β, which then phosphorylates IκB allowing for K48 ubiquitination: leads to proteasomal degradation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Rel A and p50 can then enter the nucleus and bind the NF-κB response element.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] This coupled with NFAT signaling allows for complete activation of the IL-2 gene.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] While in most cases activation is dependent on TCR recognition of antigen, alternative pathways for activation have been described.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] For example, cytotoxic T cells have been shown to become activated when targeted by other CD8 T cells leading to tolerization of the latter.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] In spring 2014, the T-Cell Activation in Space (TCAS) experiment was launched to the International Space Station on the SpaceX CRS-3 mission to study how "deficiencies in the human immune system are affected by a microgravity environment".
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cell activation is modulated by reactive oxygen species.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] A unique feature of T cells is their ability to discriminate between healthy and abnormal (e.g. infected or cancerous) cells in the body.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Healthy cells typically express a large number of self derived pMHC on their cell surface and although the T cell antigen receptor can interact with at least a subset of these self pMHC, the T cell generally ignores these healthy cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] However, when these very same cells contain even minute quantities of pathogen derived pMHC, T cells are able to become activated and initiate immune responses.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The ability of T cells to ignore healthy cells but respond when these same cells contain pathogen (or cancer) derived pMHC is known as antigen discrimination.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The molecular mechanisms that underlie this process are controversial.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Causes of T cell deficiency include lymphocytopenia of T cells and/or defects on function of individual T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Complete insufficiency of T cell function can result from hereditary conditions such as severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID), Omenn syndrome, and cartilage–hair hypoplasia.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The main pathogens of concern in T cell deficiencies are intracellular pathogens, including *Herpes simplex virus*, *Mycobacterium* and *Listeria*.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Also, fungal infections are also more common and severe in T cell deficiencies.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Cancer of T cells is termed T-cell lymphoma, and accounts for perhaps one in ten cases of non-Hodgkin lymphoma.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cell exhaustion is a poorly defined or ambiguous term.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] There are three approaches to its definition.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] "The first approach primarily defines as exhausted the cells that present the same cellular dysfunction (typically, the absence of an expected effector response).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] The second approach primarily defines as exhausted the cells that are produced by a given cause (typically, but not necessarily, chronic exposure to an antigen).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Finally, the third approach primarily defines as exhausted the cells that present the same molecular markers (typically, programmed cell death protein 1 [PD-1])." Indeed, it is now starting to emerge that exhaustion might not be the only T cell dysfunctional state.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] In fact, tolerization, anergy, cell death, ignorance, senesence and exclusion have recently emerged as additional sources and/or states of T cell dysfunction in cancer and chronic viral infection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Dysfunctional T cells are characterized by progressive loss of function, changes in transcriptional profiles and sustained expression of inhibitory receptors.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] At first, cells lose their ability to produce IL-2 and TNFα, which is followed by the loss of high proliferative capacity and cytotoxic potential, and eventually leads to their deletion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Exhausted T cells typically indicate higher levels of CD43, CD69 and inhibitory receptors combined with lower expression of CD62L and CD127.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Exhaustion can develop during chronic infections, sepsis and cancer.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Exhausted T cells preserve their functional exhaustion even after repeated antigen exposure.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cell exhaustion can be triggered by several factors like persistent antigen exposure and lack of CD4 T cell help.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Antigen exposure also has effect on the course of exhaustion because longer exposure time and higher viral load increases the severity of T cell exhaustion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] At least 2–4 weeks exposure is needed to establish exhaustion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Another factor able to induce exhaustion are inhibitory receptors including programmed cell death protein 1 (PD1), CTLA-4, T cell membrane protein-3 (TIM3), and lymphocyte activation gene 3 protein (LAG3).
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Soluble molecules such as cytokines IL-10 or TGF-β are also able to trigger exhaustion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Last known factors that can play a role in T cell exhaustion are regulatory cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Treg cells can be a source of IL-10 and TGF-β and therefore they can play a role in T cell exhaustion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Furthermore, T cell exhaustion is reverted after depletion of Treg cells and blockade of PD1.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cell exhaustion can also occur during sepsis as a result of cytokine storm.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Later after the initial septic encounter anti-inflammatory cytokines and pro-apoptotic proteins take over to protect the body from damage.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Sepsis also carries high antigen load and inflammation.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] In this stage of sepsis T cell exhaustion increases.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Currently there are studies aiming to utilize inhibitory receptor blockades in treatment of sepsis.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] While during infection T cell exhaustion can develop following persistent antigen exposure after graft transplant similar situation arises with alloantigen presence.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] It was shown that T cell response diminishes over time after kidney transplant.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] These data suggest T cell exhaustion plays an important role in tolerance of a graft mainly by depletion of alloreactive CD8 T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Several studies showed positive effect of chronic infection on graft acceptance and its long-term survival mediated partly by T cell exhaustion.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] It was also shown that recipient T cell exhaustion provides sufficient conditions for NK cell transfer.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] While there are data showing that induction of T cell exhaustion can be beneficial for transplantation it also carries disadvantages among which can be counted increased number of infections and the risk of tumor development.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] During cancer T cell exhaustion plays a role in tumor protection.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] According to research some cancer-associated cells as well as tumor cells themselves can actively induce T cell exhaustion at the site of tumor.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] T cell exhaustion can also play a role in cancer relapses as was shown on leukemia.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Some studies have suggested that it is possible to predict relapse of leukemia based on expression of inhibitory receptors PD-1 and TIM-3 by T cells.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] During chronic antigen stimulation in tumors, metabolic reprogramming becomes defective; progressive glucose deprivation and altered lipid metabolism accelerate T-cell exhaustion and blunt the efficacy of checkpoint blockade therapies.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Many experiments and clinical trials have focused on immune checkpoint blockers in cancer therapy, with some of these approved as valid therapies that are now in clinical use.
[src:adaptive-immunity/t-cell] Inhibitory receptors targeted by those medical procedures are vital in T cell exhaustion and blocking them can reverse these changes.
